value.value: The reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of an oviduct over time, from its formation to the mature structure. An oviduct is a tube through which an ova passes from the ovary to the uterus, or from the ovary to the outside of the organism.
The reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cervix over time, from its formation to the mature structure.
The reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of the vagina over time, from its formation to the mature structure.
The regulation of body fluids process in which parasympathetic nerves stimulate the bladder wall muscle to contract and expel urine from the body.
A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell increases the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.
A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell reduces the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.
Any process that modulates the potential difference across a post-synaptic membrane.

A process that leads to a temporary increase in postsynaptic potential due to the flow of positively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell. The flow of ions that causes an EPSP is an excitatory postsynaptic current (EPSC) and makes it easier for the neuron to fire an action potential.

A process that causes a temporary decrease in postsynaptic membrane potential due to the flow of negatively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell. The flow of ions that causes an IPSP is an inhibitory postsynaptic current (IPSC) and makes it more difficult for the neuron to fire an action potential.
The reflex process in which a mechanical stimulus applied to the eye elicits a response of the eyelid closing.

label.value: smooth muscle contraction involved in micturition

value.value: The process leading to shortening and/or development of tension in the urinary bladder smooth muscle tissue involved in the expulsion urine from the body.
The process of communication from a neuron to a smooth muscle in the bladder that contributes to the expulsion of urine from the body.
A compound molecular function in which an effector function is controlled by one or more regulatory components.

The binding activity of a molecule that brings together two or more molecules through a selective, non-covalent, often stoichiometric interaction, permitting those molecules to function in a coordinated way.
A nonmotile primary cilium that is found at the apical surface of auditory receptor cells. The kinocilium is surrounded by actin-based stereocilia.
The regulated release of serotonin by a cell, in which released serotonin acts as a neurotransmitter.

The process in which relatively unspecialized cells, acquire specialized structural and/or functional features of inner ear receptor cells. Inner ear receptor cells are mechanorecptors found in the inner ear responsible for transducing signals involved in balance and sensory perception of sound.
The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a vestibular hair cell.
Any process that alters the size or shape of a vestibular receptor cell.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an auditory receptor cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a vestibular receptor cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an inner ear receptor cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of growth hormone from a cell.

label.value: positive regulation of growth hormone secretion

value.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of growth hormone from a cell.

label.value: negative regulation of growth hormone secretion

value.value: Any process that decreases or stops the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of growth hormone from a cell.

The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized structural and/or functional features of a somatotropin secreting cell. A somatotropin secreting cell is an acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces growth hormone, somatotropin.

The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized structural and/or functional features of a prolactin secreting cell. A prolactin secreting cell is an acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces prolactin.

The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized structural and/or functional features of a corticotropic hormone secreting cell. An corticotropic hormone secreting cell is a basophil cell of the anterior pituitary that produces corticotropin.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a corticotropic hormone secreting cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. An corticotropic hormone secreting cell is a basophil cell of the anterior pituitary that produces corticotropin.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a prolactin secreting cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A prolactin secreting cell is an acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces prolactin.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a somatotropin secreting cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A somatotropin secreting cell is an acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces growth hormone, somatotropin.
The process in which a startle magnitude is reduced when the startling stimulus is preceded by a low-intensity prepulse.

label.value: maternal process involved in female pregnancy

value.value: A reproductive process occurring in the mother that allows an embryo or fetus to develop within it.

label.value: embryonic process involved in female pregnancy

value.value: A reproductive process occurring in the embryo or fetus that allows the embryo or fetus to develop within the mother.

label.value: regulation of syncytium formation by plasma membrane fusion

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a syncytium, a mass of cytoplasm containing several nuclei enclosed within a single plasma membrane, by the fusion of the plasma membranes of two or more individual cells.

label.value: positive regulation of syncytium formation by plasma membrane fusion

value.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a syncytium, a mass of cytoplasm containing several nuclei enclosed within a single plasma membrane, by the fusion of the plasma membranes of two or more individual cells.

A reflex that occurs in response to suckling, beginning with a nerve impulse from a receptor in the mammary gland and ending with the ejection of milk from the gland. Signaling never reaches a level of consciousness.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the urinary bladder over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The urinary bladder is an elastic, muscular sac situated in the anterior part of the pelvic cavity in which urine collects before excretion.

The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of the olfactory pit from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the olfactory pit, which is an indentation of the olfactory placode, and ends when the pits hollows out to form the nasopharynx.

label.value: regulation of adenosine receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the adenosine receptor signaling pathway. The adenosine receptor pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an adenosine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

label.value: positive regulation of adenosine receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the adenosine receptor signaling pathway. The adenosine receptor pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an adenosine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

label.value: negative regulation of adenosine receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the adenosine receptor signaling pathway. The adenosine receptor pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an adenosine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a cilium.

definition.value: Note that cilia and eukaryotic flagella are deemed to be equivalent.

value.value: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a limb over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A limb is an appendage of an animal used for locomotion or grasping. Examples include legs, arms or some types of fin.

The process pertaining to the initial formation of a limb bud from unspecified parts. This process begins with the formation of a local condensation of mesenchyme cells within the prospective limb field, and ends when a limb bud is recognizable.
The opening and spreading out of the outer ear.
The growth of the outer ear.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of lipase activity, the hydrolysis of a lipid or phospholipid.
Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of lipase activity, the hydrolysis of a lipid or phospholipid.
Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of lipase activity, the hydrolysis of a lipid or phospholipid.
